The '''Natal Organisation of Women''' (NOW) was a regional women's organization in [[South Africa]] in the [[KwaZulu-Natal|Natal]] area. NOW was founded in 1983 and affiliated with the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] (UDF).<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HwqQCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA202&dq=%22natal%20organisation%20of%20women%22&pg=PA202#v=onepage&q=%22natal%20organisation%20of%20women%22&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa|last=Sheldon|first=Kathleen|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2016|isbn=9781442262935|edition=2nd|location=|pages=202|via=}}</ref> NOW included women from all ages, class and races.{{Sfn|Hassim|2006|p=134}} NOW's values were in opposition of those expressed by the [[Inkatha Freedom Party|Inkatha's]] women's groups.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3vZwrz6-0H8C&lpg=PA235&ots=j8rjCDM6Ho&dq=%22natal%20organisation%20of%20women%22&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q=%22natal%20organisation%20of%20women%22&f=false|title=Women and the Remaking of Politics in Southern Africa: Negotiating Autonomy, Incorporation and Representation|last=Geisler|first=Gisela|publisher=Nordic Africa Institute|year=2005|isbn=9789171065155|location=|pages=72|via=}}</ref>
== History == Since 1980, women felt that there was a need for "an ongoing programme that would unite women and deal with women's issues."<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/organisations/natal-organisation-women-now|title=Natal Organisation of Women (NOW)|last=|first=|date=30 March 2011|website=South African History Online|publisher=|access-date=8 September 2016}}</ref> A group of women founded NOW in December 1983.<ref name=":1" /> One of the founding members was [[Victoria Mxenge]].<ref name=":02">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7951|title=Mlungisi Griffiths Mxenge and Victoria Nonyamezelo|last=|first=|date=|website=The Presidency of South Africa|publisher=|access-date=8 September 2016}}</ref> NOW launched the group on August 9, 1984.{{Sfn|Meer|1998|p=122}} The issues they focused on included the cost of living, housing and problems surrounding maternity and childcare in South Africa.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YOHHNsobjPIC&lpg=PA283&dq=%22natal%20organisation%20of%20women%22&pg=PA283#v=onepage&q=%22natal%20organisation%20of%20women%22&f=false|title=Women in South African History: They Remove Boulders and Cross Rivers|last=Cherry|first=Janet|publisher=Human Sciences Research Council|year=2007|isbn=9780796921741|editor-last=Gasa|editor-first=Nomboniso|location=|pages=283|chapter='We Were Not Afraid': The Role of Women in the 1980s' Township Uprising in the Eastern Cape|via=}}</ref> The first branches of NOW were located in [[Durban]].<ref name=":2" /> The first president of NOW was [[Phumzile Mlambo-Ngcuka]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://psiimpact.com/2013/07/the-daily-impact-un-women-taps-former-south-african-leader/|title=The Daily Impact: UN Women Taps Former South African Leader|last=|first=|date=11 July 2013|website=Impact|publisher=|access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref> When Mxenge was killed, NOW organized a demonstration in Durban.{{Sfn|Meer|1998|p=135}}
NOW disbanded in 1990 and members joined with the [[African National Congress]] (ANC).<ref name=":0" />
