'''Status–income disequilibrium''' (sometimes [[abbreviation|abbreviated]] '''SID''') is a political term used to describe a desirable high [[social status | status]] job with relatively low [[income]]. It is a variation on the sociological term "[[status inconsistency]]". The phrase was coined by ''[[The New York Times]]'' columnist [[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]] in his 1996 article [https://www.weeklystandard.com/david-brooks/the-tragedy-of-sid "The Tragedy of SID"]. He wrote: {{quote|The sufferers of this malady, have jobs that give them high status but low income. They lunch on an expense account at [[The Palm (restaurant)|The Palm]], but dine at home on macaroni. All day long the phone-message slips pile up on their desks—calls from famous people seeking favors—but at night they realize the tub needs scrubbing, so it's down on the hands and knees with the Ajax. At work they are aristocrats, Kings of the [[Meritocracy]], schmoozing with [[Felix Rohatyn]]. At home they are peasants, wondering if they can really afford to have orange juice every morning.<ref>[https://www.weeklystandard.com/david-brooks/the-tragedy-of-sid David Brooks, "The Tragedy of SID"], ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', May 6, 1996.</ref>}}
David Brooks characterized the "sufferers" from SID in a long list, which includes [[News program|TV news]] producers, [[museum curator]]s, [[classical music]] performers, [[Executive Office of the President of the United States|White House aides]], and politicians, among others. Other journalists applied the term to "authors and academics",<ref>[http://www.newstatesman.com/node/160908 NS essay – The honours system, far from being abolished, should be hugely expanded], by [[Richard Reeves (American writer)|Richard Reeves]], ''[[New Statesman]]'', 08 November, 2004.</ref> journalists,<ref>[http://www.slate.com/id/2132709/ Are Journalists Underpaid?], by [[Daniel Gross]], ''[[Slate Magazine]]'', December 20, 2005.</ref> writers,<ref>[http://business.theatlantic.com/2009/05/debt_a_writers_life.php Debt: A Writer's Life], by [[Megan McArdle]], ''[[The Atlantic]]'', 15 May 2009.</ref> "[[British middle class]]es",<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3635427/The-Coping-Classes---Part-1-Why-do-we-all-feel-so-damn-poor.html The Coping Classes – Part 1], by Judith Woods, ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 31 January 2008</ref> and even to the [[List of United Kingdom MPs|British MPs]].<ref>[http://www.slate.com/id/2219044/ No, You May Not Put My Taxes Toward Your Floating Duck House], [[Anne Applebaum]], ''[[Slate Magazine]]'', May 26, 2009.</ref>
